"issues/27389)"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:8
msgid ""
"Add support to the compiler to override the default allocator, allowing a "
"different allocator to be used by default in Rust programs. Additionally, "
"also switch the default allocator for dynamic libraries and static libraries "
"to using the system malloc instead of jemalloc."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:13 src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:241
msgid ""
"_Note:_ this RFC has been superseded by [RFC 1974](https://github.com/rust-"
"lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/1974-global-allocators.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:15
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:17
msgid ""
"Note that this issue was [discussed quite a bit](http://smallcultfollowing."
"com/babysteps/blog/2014/11/14/allocators-in-rust/) in the past, and the meat "
"of this RFC draws from Niko's post."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:22
msgid ""
"Currently all Rust programs by default use jemalloc for an allocator because "
"it is a fairly reasonable default as it is commonly much faster than the "
"default system allocator. This is not desirable, however, when embedding "
"Rust code into other runtimes. Using jemalloc implies that Rust will be "
"using one allocator while the host application (e.g. Ruby, Firefox, etc) "
"will be using a separate allocator. Having two allocators in one process "
"generally hurts performance and is not recommended, so the Rust toolchain "
"needs to provide a method to configure the allocator."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:31
msgid ""
"In addition to using an entirely separate allocator altogether, some Rust "
"programs may want to simply instrument allocations or shim in additional "
"functionality (such as memory tracking statistics). This is currently quite "
"difficult to do, and would be accommodated with a custom allocation scheme."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:36
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:38
msgid ""
"The high level design can be found [in this gist](https://gist.github.com/"
"alexcrichton/41c6aad500e56f49abda), but this RFC intends to expound on the "
"idea to make it more concrete in terms of what the compiler implementation "
"will look like. A [sample implementation](https://github.com/alexcrichton/"
"rust/tree/less-jemalloc) is available of this section."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:46
msgid "High level design"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:48
msgid ""
"The design of this RFC from 10,000 feet (referred to below), which was "
"[previously outlined](https://gist.github.com/"
"alexcrichton/41c6aad500e56f49abda) looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:51
msgid ""
"Define a set of symbols which correspond to the APIs specified in `alloc::"
"heap`. The `liballoc` library will call these symbols directly. Note that "
"this means that each of the symbols take information like the size of "
"allocations and such."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:55
msgid ""
"Create two shim libraries which implement these allocation-related "
"functions. Each shim is shipped with the compiler in the form of a static "
"library. One shim will redirect to the system allocator, the other shim will "
"bundle a jemalloc build along with Rust shims to redirect to jemalloc."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:59
msgid ""
"Intermediate artifacts (rlibs) do not resolve this dependency, they're just "
"left dangling."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:61
msgid ""
"When producing a \"final artifact\", rustc by default links in one of two "
"shims:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:63
msgid "If we're producing a staticlib or a dylib, link the system shim."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:64
msgid ""
"If we're producing an exe and all dependencies are rlibs link the jemalloc "
"shim."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:67
msgid ""
"The final link step will be optional, and one could link in any compliant "
"allocator at that time if so desired."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:70
msgid "New Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:72
msgid "Two new **unstable** attributes will be added to the compiler:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:74
msgid ""
"`#![needs_allocator]` indicates that a library requires the \"allocation "
"symbols\" to link successfully. This attribute will be attached to "
"`liballoc` and no other library should need to be tagged as such. "
"Additionally, most crates don't need to worry about this attribute as "
"they'll transitively link to liballoc."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:79
msgid ""
"`#![allocator]` indicates that a crate is an allocator crate. This is "
"currently also used for tagging FFI functions as an \"allocation function\" "
"to leverage more LLVM optimizations as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:83
msgid ""
"All crates implementing the Rust allocation API must be tagged with `#!"
"[allocator]` to get properly recognized and handled."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:86
msgid "New Crates"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:88
msgid "Two new **unstable** crates will be added to the standard distribution:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:90
msgid ""
"`alloc_system` is a crate that will be tagged with `#![allocator]` and will "
"redirect allocation requests to the system allocator."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:92
msgid ""
"`alloc_jemalloc` is another allocator crate that will bundle a static copy "
"of jemalloc to redirect allocations to."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:95
msgid ""
"Both crates will be available to link to manually, but they will not be "
"available in stable Rust to start out."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:98
msgid "Allocation functions"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:100
msgid ""
"Each crate tagged `#![allocator]` is expected to provide the full suite of "
"allocation functions used by Rust, defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:115
msgid ""
"The exact API of all these symbols is considered **unstable** (hence the "
"leading `__`). This otherwise currently maps to what `liballoc` expects "
"today. The compiler will not currently typecheck `#![allocator]` crates to "
"ensure these symbols are defined and have the correct signature."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:120
msgid ""
"Also note that to define the above API in a Rust crate it would look "
"something like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:126
msgid "/* ... */"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:130
msgid "Limitations of `#![allocator]`"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:132
msgid ""
"Allocator crates (those tagged with `#![allocator]`) are not allowed to "
"transitively depend on a crate which is tagged with `#![needs_allocator]`. "
"This would introduce a circular dependency which is difficult to link and is "
"highly likely to otherwise just lead to infinite recursion."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:137
msgid ""
"The compiler will also not immediately verify that crates tagged with `#!"
"[allocator]` do indeed define an appropriate allocation API, and vice versa "
"if a crate defines an allocation API the compiler will not verify that it is "
"tagged with `#![allocator]`. This means that the only meaning `#!"
"[allocator]` has to the compiler is to signal that the default allocator "
"should not be linked."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:144
msgid "Default allocator specifications"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:146
msgid ""
"Target specifications will be extended with two keys: `lib_allocation_crate` "
"and `exe_allocation_crate`, describing the default allocator crate for these "
"two kinds of artifacts for each target. The compiler will by default have "
"all targets redirect to `alloc_system` for both scenarios, but "
"`alloc_jemalloc` will be used for binaries on OSX, Bitrig, DragonFly, "
"FreeBSD, Linux, OpenBSD, and GNU Windows. MSVC will notably **not** use "
"jemalloc by default for binaries (we don't currently build jemalloc on MSVC)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:154
msgid "Injecting an allocator"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:156
msgid ""
"As described above, the compiler will inject an allocator if necessary into "
"the current compilation. The compiler, however, cannot blindly do so as it "
"can easily lead to link errors (or worse, two allocators), so it will have "
"some heuristics for only injecting an allocator when necessary. The steps "
"taken by the compiler for any particular compilation will be:"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:162
msgid ""
"If no crate in the dependency graph is tagged with `#![needs_allocator]`, "
"then the compiler does not inject an allocator."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:164
msgid "If only an rlib is being produced, no allocator is injected."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:165
msgid ""
"If any crate tagged with `#[allocator]` has been explicitly linked to (e.g. "
"via an `extern crate` statement directly or transitively) then no allocator "
"is injected."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:168
msgid "If two allocators have been linked to explicitly an error is generated."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:169
msgid ""
"If only a binary is being produced, then the target's `exe_allocation_crate` "
"value is injected, otherwise the `lib_allocation_crate` is injected."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:172
msgid ""
"The compiler will also record that the injected crate is injected, so later "
"compilations know that rlibs don't actually require the injected crate at "
"runtime (allowing it to be overridden)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:176
msgid "Allocators in practice"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:178
msgid ""
"Most libraries written in Rust wouldn't interact with the scheme proposed in "
"this RFC at all as they wouldn't explicitly link with an allocator and "
"generally are compiled as rlibs. If a Rust dynamic library is used as a "
"dependency, then its original choice of allocator is propagated throughout "
"the crate graph, but this rarely happens (except for the compiler itself, "
"which will continue to use jemalloc)."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:185
msgid ""
"Authors of crates which are embedded into other runtimes will start using "
"the system allocator by default with no extra annotation needed. If they "
"wish to funnel Rust allocations to the same source as the host application's "
"allocations then a crate can be written and linked in."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:190
msgid ""
"Finally, providers of allocators will simply provide a crate to do so, and "
"then applications and/or libraries can make explicit use of the allocator by "
"depending on it as usual."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:194
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:196
msgid ""
"A significant amount of API surface area is being added to the compiler and "
"standard distribution as part of this RFC, but it is possible for it to all "
"enter as `#[unstable]`, so we can take our time stabilizing it and perhaps "
"only stabilize a subset over time."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:201
msgid ""
"The limitation of an allocator crate not being able to link to the standard "
"library (or libcollections) may be a somewhat significant hit to the "
"ergonomics of defining an allocator, but allocators are traditionally a very "
"niche class of library and end up defining their own data structures "
"regardless."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:206
msgid ""
"Libraries on crates.io may accidentally link to an allocator and not "
"actually use any specific API from it (other than the standard allocation "
"symbols), forcing transitive dependants to silently use that allocator."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:210
msgid ""
"This RFC does not specify the ability to swap out the allocator via the "
"command line, which is certainly possible and sometimes more convenient than "
"modifying the source itself."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:214
msgid ""
"It's possible to define an allocator API (e.g. define the symbols) but then "
"forget the `#![allocator]` annotation, causing the compiler to wind up "
"linking two allocators, which may cause link errors that are difficult to "
"debug."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:218
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:220
msgid ""
"The compiler's knowledge about allocators could be simplified quite a bit to "
"the point where a compiler flag is used to just turn injection on/off, and "
"then it's the responsibility of the application to define the necessary "
"symbols if the flag is turned off. The current implementation of this RFC, "
"however, is not seen as overly invasive and the benefits of \"everything's "
"just a crate\" seems worth it for the mild amount of complexity in the "
"compiler."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:227
msgid ""
"Many of the names (such as `alloc_system`) have a number of alternatives, "
"and the naming of attributes and functions could perhaps follow a stronger "
"convention."
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:231
msgid "Unresolved questions"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:233
msgid ""
"Does this enable jemalloc to be built without a prefix on Linux? This would "
"enable us to direct LLVM allocations to jemalloc, which would be quite nice!"
msgstr ""

#: src/1183-swap-out-jemalloc.md:236
msgid ""
"Should BSD-like systems use Rust's jemalloc by default? Many of them have "
"jemalloc as the system allocator and even the special APIs we use from "
"jemalloc."
msgstr ""

